title: For Sale/Trade:  Kel Tec P40   .40 cal
location: Virginia Beach Oceanfront, Hampton Roads, Virginia
postcontent:
KelTec P-40 is a  40 S&W caliber , 3 1/4 inch barrel, fixed sights, 9 rounds and black polymer frame pistol.  It is a very powerful weight/caliber handgun. Probably the smallest/lightest .40 out here.  Because of it's size, it is an outstanding CCW.  

The P40 is no longer manufactured and is slowly becoming a hard gun to find. I have not had a problem with the rounds I have put through it (approx100) and it feeds the Golden Sabers and Hydrashocks just fine. On the range I use the Ga. Arms reloads and they work great.

Smith and Wesson 6900 series magazines work as well as long as they are factory mags.

I shot in the high 90's last qualification that I went through with it . Would of been higher but have left shoulder problem and I had to shoot 5 rounds weak hand only and threw one out.

If your scared of recoil you should not get this gun. Get a 9mm or smaller. As a lot of DAO pistols do, it has  a long trigger pull.  I like this feature myself as a CCW safety. Trust me , if your in a SHTF situation, that trigger pull will be insignificant.

This should be considered a CCW / personal protection weapon and not as a range gun.  Even though I group pretty good at 10 yards, I know that if I need to use this gun it's going to be closer to 10 feet or less and this is perfect for the P40.

It comes with 2 extra magazines and a Fobus holster.  This is a steal at this price.

The size of these plate carrier vests are adjustable from "Small to X-Large"
MIL-A-46100 steel is Military spec armor. MIL-A 46100 armor is used to stop high velocity projectiles (HVPs). This particular grade military spec armor steel is especially useful to protect structures or vehicles from sniper fire or any form of weapon that will emit the HVPs depending on the threat level, various thicknesses of steel may be required to protect vital organs.
The measurement of the plates are both
1/4" and .393" also not to mention tested by the US Army test labs.
I had ar500 plates but 46100 material is by far a lot better. Some people say AR500 are military steel but the military never uses ar500. I used a .308 rifle and a .223 at these plates at 36 and 50 yards. Then shot it with AK 47 50rnds, 5.56 30rnds, endless .357/9mm/45cal, 7.62x54R, .30-06 and a 300 win mag 3 times at 250yards, that did flatten the plate but still no penetration. Not to mention shot at it with a .45 handgun...still no penetration. This will not fail to disappoint as it this is one of the best quality steel out there. Ar500 is target material not to be used as body armor. This body armor with the 2 plates and the vest weighs a total of 12 pounds. I've shot at this multiple times with different rifles and Handguns and it still holds up. You could attach MOLLE gear to this vest such as your Hydration water Carrier, Rifle and Handgun Magazine pouches, Radio pouches, EMT Medical pouches and etc.

If you want the entire Front/Back & Side set with the carrier vest, 2 side plates, Front and back plates that would be $300.00

title: For Sale:  Remington 700 SPS Tactical AAC in AICS Accuracy International Chasis
postcontent:
Firstly, for the low ballers, don't bother, I am not going for it and you will be ignored. 
Secondly, don't short me at the FFL, I will leave.
Thirdly, don't send me an email if your email address is something shady like 420Gangster or Stoner-something, I won't respond. 
Lastly, all sales go through an FFL. 

This rifle started life as a Remington 700 SPS Tactical AAC. I still have the original box, papers, and stock (no stock screws though). I then threw an Accuracy International AICS chasis on it, Griffin muzzle brake, and a Blackhawk 20 MOA rail. I finally added a Whidden Gun Works rear monopod into the buttplate and a Caldwell bipod. Between the heavy AICS chasis and the Griffin brake, I can easily call my own shots, no spotter necessary.

A little background on some of the components:

The Remington 700 AAC SPS Tactical uses a 1:10 twist heavy barrel at 20'' threaded. According to a TTAG article, this rifle was used as their "affordable 1,000 yard gun", not sure about that as the 20'' is short. The farthest I've shot it out to is 700 yards. The AICS speaks for itself, it is a fantastic chassis and adds quite a bit of weight for benchrest and uses the best mags out there. There are some slight scratches on the stock, please consult the pictures.

The Griffin muzzle brake is a lot like a Battlecomp or a KAC Triple Tap. Extremely effective and no annoying blast to the sides. They went with holes instead of slots though. One huge benefit versus the Battlecomp is hardness, the Griffin is significantly harder.

Blackhawk 20 MOA scope rail will "add" elevation adjustment to your scope for longer range shooting. Caldwell bipod has held up to the recoil of lots of .308. I don't care much for the monopod honestly, so I don't use it much.

Discounts: Will subtract $20 to keep the bipod. Will subtract $50 to keep the mag.

title: For Sale:  AK-74 (5.45mm x 39) with mags and ammo
location: Lake of the Ozarks, Missouri, United States
postcontent:
For sale, a Saiga SGL-31-85. This is an AK-74 clone, made in Russia at the Izhmash plant out of all milled parts. Imported by FIME Group in Las Vegas; has the requisite six US-made parts to make it legal. This rifle has an original Russian barrel! (The US TAPCO barrels are less than desirable). It has a Soviet scope mount on the left side and a fully folding stock. Standard AK sights; polymer handguards. 

I purchased this rifle brand new six months ago and have only put 400 rounds through it. I am selling it very reluctantly; I am having financial difficulties and must get rid of some things that I love dearly.

The rifle will come with all of my 5.45mm ammo; one sealed crate of 2,160 rounds, another spam can of 1,080 rounds, and a fifty cal can with about 800 rounds. All but 300 rounds is mil surplus 7N6 53-grain FMJ; the 300 rounds portion is WPA 60-grain FMJ (I had that for my SHTF ammo). Also comes with 7 original Bulgarian 30-round mags, and a plastic rifle case.

Between the rifle, mags, and ammo, I have about two grand tied up in it; I'm looking for $1500. With the imposition of economic sanctions on Russia, no one knows the status of future firearm imports.

I will only sell in person, and am willing to drive two hours. This puts me in Kansas City, Mountain Grove, Nevada, Columbia, and anywhere in that circle.

Any questions, just email me. Thanks for looking.
